hci.rules\r\nReading rules file: /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/99-gnss.rules\r\nReading rules file: /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/99-libsane1.rules\r\nReading rules file: /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/99-systemd.rules\r\nDEVPATH=/bus/usb/drivers/cdc_wdm\r\nACTION=add\r\nSUBSYSTEM=drivers\r\nUSEC_INITIALIZED=161571608\r\nUnload kernel module index.\r\nUnloaded link configuration context.\r\n```\r\nThey look pretty similar to me, but without fail if the linked patch is installed the modem's USB device doesn't show up at all in `lsusb`.\n", "source": "github_issue", "formatting_done": true}
{"text": "Title: sd-journal: find a smart way to order log lines from different boots if neither has a useful wallclock time.\n\nBody:\nI use a RaspberryPi2 with Archlinux and systemd version 219 to 222 (since the beginning of June until now).\nThe RaspberryPi does not have an RTC (real time clock).\nThe missing RTC results in the first log messages of every boot to be of the same date and more or less from the same time of day. Here you see an excerpt from my logs as seen with `journalctl`.\n(The ellipsis were inserted by myself.)\n\n```\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:07 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 54.9M free of 361.8M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\nJan 01 01:00:07 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Permanent journal is using 104.0M (max allowed 256.0M, trying to leave 2.1G free of 11.7G available \u2192 current limit 256.0M).\nJan 01 01:00:07 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Time spent on flushing to /var is 5.756ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 55.0M free of 362.3M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Permanent journal is using 40.0M (max allowed 1.4G, trying to leave 2.1G free of 12.2G available \u2192 current limit 1.4G).\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[117]: Time spent on flushing to /var is 5.777ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[126]: Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 54.9M free of 361.8M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi kernel: raid6: neonx2     394 MB/s\n...\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[126]: Permanent journal is using 88.0M (max allowed 256.0M, trying to leave 2.1G free of 11.7G available \u2192 current limit 256.0M).\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd[1]: Mounted POSIX Message Queue File System.\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd-journal[126]: Time spent on flushing to /var is 7.557ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd[1]: Mounted Debug File System.\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi kernel: raid6: using algorithm neonx4 (433 MB/s)\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi kernel: raid6: using intx1 recovery algorithm\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi systemd[1]: Mounted Temporary Directory.\n-- Reboot --\nJan 01 01:00:08 gemipi kernel: bcm2708-dmaengine 3f007000.dma: DMA legacy API manager at f3007000, dmachans=0x7f35\n```\n\nAs you can see, there are many boots which have only one line of logs, which do not even start with the usual \"Runtime journal is ...\" line.\nThis is certainly not correct.\n\nFurthermore, at the first boot permanent journal is using 104.0M, at the second boot permanent journal is using only 40.0M. That does not make sense, chronologically. The messages were probably generated in the reverse chronological order.\nI think that journald should guarantee that log-messages which are generated in some chronological order are displayed by journalctl in the same chronological order.\n\nI suspect that `journalctl` is mixing up different boots when merging different `.journal` files.\n\n\n--- Comment by poettering ---\nthe journal will order the journal log lines by their sequence number if possible, but it can only do so, if it detects that the messages are from the same system. If that doesn't work, it will order by monotonic time if possible, but it can only do so if it detects that the messages to be from the same boot, as determined by the boot id /proc/sys/kernel/random/boot_id. It will then fall back to ordering by wallclock time, as last resort.\n\nAre you using an initrd or so, that carries a different /etc/machine-id or so? Is this some weird/stateless setup, where /etc is not persistent or so?\n\nCould you please get me the journalctl output for the exact same lines as above, but with \"-o verbose\" specified? That will show all the individual log message fields, with all the data that is used to order the lines. THanks.\n\n--- Comment by jaystrictor ---\nI am using the standard system provided by http://archlinuxarm.org, nothing fancy.\n\nHonestly, I do not know much about the boot process of the RaspberryPi. There does not seem to exists an initrd, at least there is no such file in `/boot` and the package `mkinitcpio` is not installed.\n\nThis is not a stateless setup. `/etc` and all the other usual directories are written to an SD-card.\n\nThe messages from the **exact same** lines as above with `-o verbose`:\n\n```\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:07.205817 CET [s=190c51237ba64e5aa45c64522a6069b1;i=1;b=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17;m=6df3bc;t=6df3b9;x=21a34ced5dbea49e]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE=Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 54.9M free of 361.8M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:07.420909 CET [s=190c51237ba64e5aa45c64522a6069b1;i=2;b=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17;m=713bf0;t=713bed;x=e319325dc5169285]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Permanent journal is using 104.0M (max allowed 256.0M, trying to leave 2.1G free of 11.7G available \u2192 current limit 256.0M).\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:07.428601 CET [s=190c51237ba64e5aa45c64522a6069b1;i=3;b=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17;m=7159fb;t=7159f9;x=893ba43d2ebd2648]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=7a5c630be79f49a89b58f3ba4aa2bf17\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Time spent on flushing to /var is 5.756ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.239101 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=1;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=7db800;t=7db7fd;x=592af6d99572db94]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE=Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 55.0M free of 362.3M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.411764 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=2;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=805a77;t=805a74;x=f64e0a80cf8df79d]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Permanent journal is using 40.0M (max allowed 1.4G, trying to leave 2.1G free of 12.2G available \u2192 current limit 1.4G).\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.419685 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=3;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=807969;t=807965;x=c6ed1bcb03309e6a]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    _PID=117\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Time spent on flushing to /var is 5.777ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.462128 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=1;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=811f34;t=811f30;x=7a6e18f80d36b2a4]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE=Runtime journal is using 4.5M (max allowed 36.6M, trying to leave 54.9M free of 361.8M available \u2192 current limit 36.6M).\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=126\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.462248 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=67;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=811fab;t=811fa8;x=d383d7ce2867862f]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=0\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=kernel\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=2695722\n    MESSAGE=raid6: neonx2     394 MB/s\n...\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.661060 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=2;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=84284a;t=842844;x=8d813705699ebd7f]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    MESSAGE_ID=ec387f577b844b8fa948f33cad9a75e6\n    _PID=126\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Permanent journal is using 88.0M (max allowed 256.0M, trying to leave 2.1G free of 11.7G available \u2192 current limit 256.0M).\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.670449 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=164;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=844cf4;t=844cf1;x=63cfa4624bec2ece]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=3\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=systemd\n    SYSLOG_PID=1\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=8877716\n    MESSAGE=Mounted POSIX Message Queue File System.\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.670977 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=3;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=844f05;t=844f01;x=5cefec7c668f65c3]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _TRANSPORT=driver\n    _PID=126\n    _UID=0\n    _GID=0\n    _COMM=systemd-journal\n    _EXE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CMDLINE=/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-journald\n    _CAP_EFFECTIVE=25402800cf\n    _SYSTEMD_CGROUP=/system.slice/systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_UNIT=systemd-journald.service\n    _SYSTEMD_SLICE=system.slice\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    MESSAGE=Time spent on flushing to /var is 7.557ms for 2 entries.\n...\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.697683 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=165;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=84b755;t=84b753;x=ad7b0bf6ba511fb1]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=3\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=systemd\n    SYSLOG_PID=1\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=8895440\n    MESSAGE=Mounted Debug File System.\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.697694 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=61;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=84b760;t=84b75e;x=ee88f7c02dfc04bc]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=0\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=kernel\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=2491039\n    MESSAGE=raid6: using algorithm neonx4 (433 MB/s)\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.697935 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=62;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=84b851;t=84b84f;x=25992bdee26182dd]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=0\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=kernel\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=2496034\n    MESSAGE=raid6: using intx1 recovery algorithm\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.698458 CET [s=6a58a99f9fc748478d9c0208dba7b552;i=166;b=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25;m=84ba5c;t=84ba5a;x=1b006962259e8212]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=97725e3422ad402c8b49824f0720ca25\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=3\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=systemd\n    SYSLOG_PID=1\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=8911369\n    MESSAGE=Mounted Temporary Directory.\n-- Reboot --\nDo 1970-01-01 01:00:08.699094 CET [s=c0f6408c59a94f229da9b67859372296;i=63;b=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44;m=84bcd8;t=84bcd6;x=4b016baf26ee4474]\n    PRIORITY=6\n    _BOOT_ID=6bfcdbf98c6f4b26ab7c06c070f71a44\n    _MACHINE_ID=20d4f52b53de4dd9aa7ac72e93285b0a\n    _HOSTNAME=gemipi\n    _TRANSPORT=kernel\n    SYSLOG_FACILITY=0\n    SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=kernel\n    _KERNEL_SUBSYSTEM=platform\n    _KERNEL_DEVICE=+platform:3f007000.dma\n    _UDEV_SYSNAME=3f007000.dma\n    _SOURCE_MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP=2501211\n    MESSAGE=bcm2708-dmaengine 3f007000.dma: DMA legacy API manager at f3007000, dmachans=0x7f35\n```\n\n--- Comment by jaystrictor ---\nI know it has been some time...\nBut can you parse the above output? What is the problem in this case? Is it possible that different boots get the same BOOT_ID?\n\n--- Comment by poettering ---\nI think systemd is really actually doing the right thing here...\n\nSo here's what happens: each time you reboot, you start with a date in 1970, and a newly randomized boot id. A couple of messages are generated this way for each boot.\n\nDuring display journalctl will now see this data, and try to make sense of it, and interleave it. Interleaving means it needs to sort the lines together, and put older data before newer data. To do that it tries to compare sequence numbers first. Sequence numbers are maintained in memory, and are reset to zero on each boot. They hence can be compared only if the boot ID matches between the two lines to compare. Since the boot ID is different for your reboots (obviously, and rightfully), this logic of ordering cannot be used. Next, journalctl tries to order things by the monotonic timestamp (i.e. the time passed since boot). Such ordering only works under the same conditions: we can only ordering lines of the same boot via the monotonic time. Which means we resort to the last way of comparing two lines: via the wallclock time. But that is always 1970, and hence results in the interleaving you see, where the lines are all mixed up.\n\nNow, the \"-- Reboot --\" lines are inserted each time the boot ID changes between two subsequent lines. And that changes _all_ the time of course, given the lines are all mixed up into one stream...\n\nNow, that's the explanation for what you see.\n\nI am not sure at all what we can do about this really. Basically, all log lines generated before the wallclock is properly set up cannot be properly ordered against lines from other boots, because we cannot derive any relationship between those individual lines at all...\n\nthe only thing I could think of is adding some kludge that tries to order lines by boot id if we detect dates before 1975 or so: if so, we'll check the newest log line generated with the same boot id, and use it's wallclock timestamp to derive an order between boot ids, and thus an order between two lines of different boot ids, if that makes any sense? But that'd be kinda nasty...\n\nOpen for ideas...\n\n--- Comment by jaystrictor ---\n> I think systemd is really actually doing the right thing here...\n\nI disagree.\nI think systemd fails to deliver readable log messages where traditional logging systems like `syslog` prevail.\nI do not trust journalctl any more and therefore stopped using it, which really is a pity.\n\nIn my opinion, systemd should **guarantee** that log messages are displayed by journalctl in the same chronological order in which they were generated.\n\nThat's a simple invariant, that every human being intuitively expects when reading logs.\n\n> So here's what happens: each time you reboot, you start with a date in 1970, and a newly randomized boot id. A couple of messages are generated this way for each boot.\n\nSo each boot gets assigned a new random boot id. Are you sure that on an embedded system, that this boot id is really random and not potentially recurring?\n\n> During display journalctl will now see this data, and try to make sense of it, and interleave it. Interleaving means it needs to sort the lines together, and put older data before newer data. To do that it tries to compare sequence numbers first. Sequence numbers are maintained in memory, and are reset to zero on each boot. They hence can be compared only if the boot ID matches between the two lines to compare. Since the boot ID is different for your reboots (obviously, and rightfully), this logic of ordering cannot be used. Next, journalctl tries to order things by the monotonic timestamp (i.e. the time passed since boot). Such ordering only works under the same conditions: we can only ordering lines of the same boot via the monotonic time. Which means we resort to the last way of comparing two lines: via the wallclock time. But that is always 1970, and hence results in the interleaving you see, where the lines are all mixed up.\n\nSo what you are essentially saying here beneath the technical aspects is:\n\"systemd tries to put older data before newer data, ..., but it fails.\"\n\n> Now, the \"-- Reboot --\" lines are inserted each time the boot ID changes between two subsequent lines. And that changes all the time of course, given the lines are all mixed up into one stream...\n\nExactly! So here you also recognize the difference between\n`the \"-- Reboot --\" lines are inserted each time the boot ID changes`\nand\n`the \"-- Reboot --\" lines are inserted each time the machine reboots`.\nThe first is the actual behavior, the second the desired behavior.\n\n> Now, that's the explanation for what you see.\n> \n> I am not sure at all what we can do about this really. Basically, all log lines generated before the wallclock is properly set up cannot be properly ordered against lines from other boots, because we cannot derive any relationship between those individual lines at all...\n> \n> the only thing I could think of is adding some kludge that tries to order lines by boot id if we detect dates before 1975 or so: if so, we'll check the newest log line generated with the same boot id, and use it's wallclock timestamp to derive an order between boot ids, and thus an order between two lines of different boot ids, if that makes any sense? But that'd be kinda nasty...\n> \n> Open for ideas...\n\nOK, here are my ideas:\nWhat exactly is the reason for resetting sequence numbers on boot? syslog for example does not do this. They have an implicit sequence number that withstands every reboot. Their implicit sequence number is just the line number of the logfile.\nCould systemd do some similar mechanism? (perhaps more explicitely than line numbers)\nI have some suggestions how one could do that:\n- As soon as systemd can read from the saved journal on disk, read out the last sequence number of the last boot and rewrite the log messages in queue to be written to disk. (seems nasty)\n- Save the order of the boot ids to the journal. You would want to generate an order on all boot ids that occur in a single journal file and save it in the same journal file. After every reboot, the order should be updated. If the boot ids are really unique and not recurring, I would prefer this method.\n\n", "source": "github_issue", "formatting_done": true}
{"text": "Title: make systemd more musl friendly\n\nBody:\n### systemd version the issue has been seen with\n\n3ec92f2f7419ce5c27422b3b2023b841cbe5bf90\n\n### Used distribution\n\nN/A\n\n### Linux kernel version used\n\n6.13.4\n\n### CPU architectures issue was seen on\n\nx86_64\n\n### Component\n\nsystemd\n\n### Expected behaviour you didn't see\n\nA successful build.\n\n### Unexpected behaviour you saw\n\n```\nclang -cc1 version 21.0.0git based upon LLVM 21.0.0git default target x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\nignoring nonexistent directory \"/<pathToSysroot>/usr/local/include\"\nignoring nonexistent directory \"/<pathToSysroot>/include\"\nignoring duplicate directory \"/<pathToSysroot>/usr/include\"\n  as it is a non-system directory that duplicates a system directory\n#include \"...\" search starts here:\n#include <...> search starts here:\n src/basic/libbasic.a.p\n src/basic\n <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic\n src/fundamental\n <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/fundamental\n src/systemd\n <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/systemd\n src/version\n <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/version\n <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/include\n /<pathToSysroot>/usr/include\n /<pathToToolchain>/lib/clang/21/include\nEnd of search list.\nIn file included from <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/af-list.c:6:\nIn file included from <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/af-list.h:4:\n<pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/forward.h:60:9: error: unknown type name '__socklen_t'; did you mean 'socklen_t'?\n   60 | typedef __socklen_t socklen_t;\n      |         ^~~~~~~~~~~\n      |         socklen_t\n/<pathToSysroot>/usr/include/bits/alltypes.h:367:18: note: 'socklen_t' declared here\n  367 | typedef unsigned socklen_t;\n      |                  ^\n```\nRe: https://github.com/systemd/systemd/commit/686bbf1e7ff7492a86f48d4b9877c2cfb5deca53#diff-6bc82d809a992789a846067c0ffb229fd6aaee159527977c60e7f2a134a87412\n\n### Steps to reproduce the problem\n\nSetup and compile for a musl-based system.\n```\n\"/<pathToToolchain>/bin/clang-21\" -cc1 -triple x86_64-pc-linux-musl -emit-obj -disable-free -clear-ast-before-backend -disable-llvm-verifier -discard-value-names -main-file-name af-list.c -mrelocation-model pic -pic-level 2 -fhalf-no-semantic-interposition -mframe-pointer=all -relaxed-aliasing -ffp-contract=on -fno-rounding-math -mconstructor-aliases -funwind-tables=2 -target-cpu x86-64 -tune-cpu generic -debug-info-kind=constructor -dwarf-version=5 -debugger-tuning=gdb -fdebug-compilation-dir=/<pathToBuildDir> -v -fcoverage-compilation-dir=/<pathToBuildDir> -resource-dir /<pathToToolchain>/lib/clang/21 -dependency-file src/basic/libbasic.a.p/af-list.c.o.d -MT src/basic/libbasic.a.p/af-list.c.o -sys-header-deps -include config.h -isystem <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/include -I src/basic/libbasic.a.p -I src/basic -I <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic -I src/fundamental -I <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/fundamental -I src/systemd -I <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/systemd -I src/version -I <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/version -I /<pathToSysroot>/usr/include -D _FILE_OFFSET_BITS=64 -isysroot /<pathToSysroot> -internal-isystem /<pathToSysroot>/usr/local/include -internal-externc-isystem /<pathToSysroot>/include -internal-externc-isystem /<pathToSysroot>/usr/include -internal-isystem /<pathToToolchain>/lib/clang/21/include -O0 -Wall -Winvalid-pch -Wextra -Wno-missing-field-initializers -Wno-unknown-warning-option -Wno-unused-parameter -Warray-bounds -Wdate-time -Wendif-labels -Werror=format=2 -Werror=format-signedness -Werror=implicit-function-declaration -Werror=implicit-int -Werror=incompatible-pointer-types -Werror=int-conversion -Werror=missing-declarations -Werror=missing-prototypes -Werror=overflow -Werror=override-init -Werror=pointer-sign -Werror=return-type -Werror=shift-count-overflow -Werror=undef -Wfloat-equal -Winit-self -Wmissing-include-dirs -Wmissing-noreturn -Wnested-externs -Wold-style-definition -Wpointer-arith -Wredundant-decls -Wshadow -Wstrict-aliasing=2 -Wstrict-prototypes -Wunused-function -Wwrite-strings -Wzero-as-null-pointer-constant -Wno-error=#warnings -Wno-string-plus-int -Wno-typedef-redefinition -Wno-gnu-variable-sized-type-not-at-end -Werror=shadow -std=gnu17 -fconst-strings -ferror-limit 19 -fvisibility=default -fstrict-flex-arrays=1 -pthread -stack-protector 2 -stack-protector-buffer-size 4 -fgnuc-version=4.2.1 -fskip-odr-check-in-gmf -fcolor-diagnostics -faddrsig -D__GCC_HAVE_DWARF2_CFI_ASM=1 -o src/basic/libbasic.a.p/af-list.c.o -x c <pathToWorktree>/systemd/src/basic/af-list.c\n```\nglibc: /usr/include/bits/types.h; `__STD_TYPE __U32_TYPE __socklen_t;`\nmusl:  no such thing\n\nMy desire was to have an LLVM-based toolchained system only, and that would need to be built with musl, as I understand building with glibc would be problematic (nevermind their own libc).\nI do hope this is a one-off catch of something new and not representative of other headaches that may come down the line after getting past this.\n\nEDIT0: I'll address my own concern about other headaches, \"printf.h\" was the next issue, and a search here brought me to https://github.com/systemd/systemd/issues/2672#issuecomment-186492067\nI guess that still applies today and systemd simply won't be built under anything other than glibc. Disappointed.\n\nEdit1: I was informed about Yocto, and had been looking what that was all about, and saw a relation to musl/systemd (specific to the `printf.h` issue, as well as other patches): https://github.com/kraj/meta-musl/blob/master/recipes-core/systemd/systemd/0024-add-fallback-parse_printf_format-implementation.patch\n\n### Additional program output to the terminal or log subsystem illustrating the issue\n\n```sh\n\n```\n\n--- Comment by richfelker ---\nThe root cause is copy&paste of a bunch of glibc header internals into the newly introduced unified forward declarations `forward.h`.\n\nThe fix is to remove these and include the proper system (libc) headers from `forward.h`. They are not expensive, and it's the only correct way to get the needed type declarations. There's no guarantee this copypasta won't eventually clash with newer versions of glibc too in subtle ways.\n\n--- Comment by richfelker ---\nAFAICT that only fixes the first of a large number of errors of the same form. Some of them may \"happen to work\" at present, but none of the copypasta declarations are valid.\n--- Comment by daandemeyer ---\nThere's two more, FILE and DIR where the benefit is a lot bigger than socklen_t  so I'm happy to take the risk of those maybe breaking in the future.\n--- Comment by richfelker ---\nThe \"benefit\" is ridiculously small, probably unmeasurable. FFS just fix it.\n\n--- Comment by yuwata ---\nI'm working on remaining issues. \n", "source": "github_issue", "formatting_done": true}
{"text": "Title: systemd unexpectedly(?) terminates units with `Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated` during a \"mount storm\"\n\nBody:\nWe have an internal customer that started experiencing unexpected restarts of certain units on their OpenShift clusters. After analyzing logs the symptoms looked very similar to [this issue](https://github.com/systemd/systemd/issues/15316), since the affected units reported `Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated` just before getting restarted. However, we already have patches for that in RHEL.\r\n\r\nAnother candidate was https://github.com/systemd/systemd/issues/30573, but I failed to reproduce that issue on multiple machines with several reproducers I could come up with. However, after putting these reproducers together with a couple of other hints from customer's logs, I was able to _conjure_ a slightly different (and _spiced up_) reproducer, that appears to reproduce the issue the customer is facing not only on RHELs, but also on Fedora Rawhide, and the latest systemd upstream (af46138f39acb55f1faefcb48ebc3316efac87b4 ATTOW, also on Rawhide). In all cases `dbus-broker` was used as the dbus... broker.\r\n\r\nReproducer:\r\n```bash\r\n#/bin/bash\r\nset -eux\r\nset -o pipefail\r\n\r\nNMOUNTS=800\r\nMPOINT=\"$(findmnt --mountpoint / --noheading -o SOURCE)\"\r\nTS=\"$(date +\"%s.%N\")\"\r\n\r\nsystemctl mask --now --runtime systemd-oomd.{socket,service}\r\nid testuser || useradd testuser\r\nsystemctl stop \"tmp-mnt*.mount\" || :\r\nsystemctl log-level debug\r\n\r\nfor i in {0..100}; do\r\n        echo \"=== $i ===\"\r\n        for i in $(seq 0 $NMOUNTS); do\r\n                mkdir -p \"/tmp/mnt$i\"\r\n                systemd-mount \"$MPOINT\" \"/tmp/mnt$i\" &\r\n        done\r\n        wait\r\n        for i in $(seq 0 $NMOUNTS); do\r\n                systemd-umount \"/tmp/mnt$i\" &\r\n        done\r\n        wait\r\n\r\n        busctl status --user --machine=testuser@ --no-pager\r\n        systemctl stop user@4711.service\r\n        (! journalctl --since=\"@$TS\" --grep \"Connection terminated\")\r\ndone\r\n```\r\n\r\nWith this reproducer I get following output in a couple of iterations (really depends on the machine you run this on and your luck):\r\n```\r\n# systemctl --version\r\nsystemd 256~devel (256~devel-gaf46138)\r\n+PAM +AUDIT +SELINUX -APPARMOR +IMA +SMACK +SECCOMP -GCRYPT +GNUTLS +OPENSSL +ACL +BLKID +CURL +ELFUTILS +FIDO2 +IDN2 -IDN +IPTC +KMOD +LIBCRYPTSETUP +LIBCRYPTSETUP_PLUGINS +LIBFDISK +PCRE2 +PWQUALITY +P11KIT +QRENCODE +TPM2 +BZIP2 +LZ4 +XZ +ZLIB +ZSTD -BPF_FRAMEWORK +XKBCOMMON +UTMP +SYSVINIT -LIBARCHIVE\r\n# ./repro.sh\r\n...\r\n++ systemctl stop user@4711.service\r\n++ journalctl --since=@1713626172.951606857 --grep 'Connection terminated'\r\n-- No entries --\r\n++ for i in {0..100}\r\n++ echo '=== 1 ==='\r\n=== 1 ===\r\n+++ seq 0 800\r\n...\r\nFailed to stop automount unit: Connection timed out\r\nFailed to stop automount unit: Connection timed out\r\nFailed to stop automount unit: Connection timed out\r\n++ busctl status --user --machine=testuser@ --no-pager\r\nBusAddress=unixexec:path=systemd-run,argv1=-M.host,argv2=-PGq,argv3=--wait,argv4=-pUser%3dtestuser,argv5=-pPAMName%3dlogin,argv6=systemd-stdio-bridge,argv7=-punix:path%3d%24%7bXDG_RUNTIME_DIR%7d/bus\r\nBusID=db15434bb5619733c1ee88f5c4c006b1\r\nPID=8351\r\nPIDFD=yes\r\nEUID=0\r\nEGID=0\r\nSupplementaryGIDs=0\r\nLabel=unconfined_u:unconfined_r:unconfined_t:s0-s0:c0.c1023\r\n++ systemctl stop user@4711.service\r\n++ journalctl --since=@1713626172.951606857 --grep 'Connection terminated'\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: systemd-hostnamed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminat>\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: systemd-logind.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: systemd-resolved.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: systemd-networkd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\nApr 20 11:25:30 xxx systemd[1]: udisks2.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\nMore details from the journal:\r\n```\r\n...\r\n[  747.889938] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=8 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  747.889987] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=9 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  747.890050] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=470 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  747.890101] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=471 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  747.890152] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=314 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  747.890199] systemd[1]: Sent message type=signal sender=org.freedesktop.systemd1 destination=n/a path=/org/freedesktop/systemd1/unit/tmp_2dmnt199_2emount interface=org.freedesktop.DBus.Properties member=PropertiesChanged cookie=315 reply_cookie=0 signature=sa{sv}as error-name=n/a error-message=n/a\r\n[  764.600613] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.687538] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  764.687805] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=systemd-homed comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[  764.736119] systemd[1]: systemd-hostnamed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.736517] audit: BPF prog-id=49 op=UNLOAD\r\n[  764.737643] systemd[1]: systemd-logind.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.738216] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.738638] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6956] caught SIGTERM, shutting down normally.\r\n[  764.739340] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6963] dhcp4 (eth0): canceled DHCP transaction\r\n[  764.739428] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6963] dhcp4 (eth0): activation: beginning transaction (timeout in 45 seconds)\r\n[  764.739488] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6963] dhcp4 (eth0): state changed no lease\r\n[  764.739568] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6965] manager: NetworkManager state is now CONNECTED_SITE\r\n[  764.741702] NetworkManager[768]: <info>  [1713626730.6988] exiting (success)\r\n[  764.785825] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=NetworkManager comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[  764.785993] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  764.834007] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.834605] avahi-daemon[744]: Got SIGTERM, quitting.\r\n[  764.835133] avahi-daemon[744]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv6 with address 2620:52:0:bb:f816:3eff:fe67:3519.\r\n[  764.835201] avahi-daemon[744]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv4 with address 10.0.187.174.\r\n[  764.835251] avahi-daemon[744]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv6 with address ::1.\r\n[  764.835321] avahi-daemon[744]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv4 with address 127.0.0.1.\r\n[  764.835399] avahi-daemon[744]: avahi-daemon 0.8 exiting.\r\n[  764.881474] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  764.881747] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=avahi-daemon comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[  764.968329] systemd[1]: systemd-resolved.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.969842] systemd[1]: systemd-networkd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.970411] systemd[1]: udisks2.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  764.970969] systemd[1]: systemd-timesyncd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe most problematic part is the unexpected NetworkManager restart (as that's how the customer noticed the issue in the first place). However, the system itself seems to be fine after this _incident_:\r\n\r\n```\r\n# systemctl status\r\n\u25cf xxx\r\n    State: running\r\n    Units: 397 loaded (incl. loaded aliases)\r\n     Jobs: 0 queued\r\n   Failed: 0 units\r\n    Since: Sat 2024-04-20 11:12:47 EDT; 18min ago\r\n  systemd: 256~devel-gaf46138\r\n   CGroup: /\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd now for the big questions - is this our issue or somebody else's (dbus-broker?)? And can we do anything about it?\r\n\r\n/cc @msekletar @rmetrich \n\n--- Comment by mrc0mmand ---\n> In all cases dbus-broker was used as the dbus... broker.\r\n\r\nJust out of curiosity, I replaced `dbus-broker` with `dbus-daemon` on the Rawhide test machine and the results are the same:\r\n\r\n```\r\n...\r\n[  974.472229] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt404.mount.\r\n[  974.500563] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt405.mount.\r\n[  974.523083] dbus-daemon[744]: [system] Failed to activate service 'org.freedesktop.systemd1': timed out (service_start_timeout=25000ms)\r\n[  974.527767] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt406.mount.\r\n[  974.555652] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt407.mount.\r\n...\r\n[  979.242541] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.242914] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1759] caught SIGTERM, shutting down normally.\r\n[  979.243545] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1765] dhcp4 (eth0): canceled DHCP transaction\r\n[  979.243663] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1765] dhcp4 (eth0): activation: beginning transaction (timeout in 45 seconds)\r\n[  979.243764] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1766] dhcp4 (eth0): state changed no lease\r\n[  979.243855] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1767] manager: NetworkManager state is now CONNECTED_SITE\r\n[  979.243957] dbus-daemon[744]: [system] Activating systemd to hand-off: service name='org.freedesktop.nm_dispatcher' unit='dbus-org.freedesktop.nm-dispatcher.service' requested by ':1.6' (uid=0 pid>\r\n[  979.245558] NetworkManager[766]: <info>  [1713629543.1787] exiting (success)\r\n[  979.255542] systemd[1]: systemd-logind.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.268549] systemd[1]: systemd-networkd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.275493] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  979.275801] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=NetworkManager comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? add>\r\n[  979.286649] systemd[1]: systemd-resolved.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.300932] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.301142] avahi-daemon[741]: Got SIGTERM, quitting.\r\n[  979.301603] avahi-daemon[741]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv6 with address 2620:52:0:bb:f816:3eff:fe67:3519.\r\n[  979.301666] avahi-daemon[741]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv4 with address 10.0.187.174.\r\n[  979.301725] avahi-daemon[741]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv6 with address ::1.\r\n[  979.301775] avahi-daemon[741]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv4 with address 127.0.0.1.\r\n[  979.305061] avahi-daemon[741]: avahi-daemon 0.8 exiting.\r\n[  979.308451] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  979.308705] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=avahi-daemon comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=>\r\n[  979.321993] systemd[1]: udisks2.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.337345] systemd[1]: systemd-timesyncd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.352637] systemd[1]: systemd-hostnamed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.368100] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[  979.379664] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[  979.379912] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=systemd-homed comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr>\r\n[  979.399167] audit: BPF prog-id=50 op=UNLOAD\r\n[  979.973431] systemd-journald[577]: [\ud83e\udc55] Suppressed 696657 messages from init.scope\r\n```\n--- Comment by mrc0mmand ---\nHere's one interesting data point: I let the reproducer run on two machines again overnight (and for the most of Sunday, so 16+ hours on each machne) after the first \"crash\", and there were no more crashes during that period. But if I reboot either of those machines and start the reproducer again, it crashes in just a couple of iterations again (and then continues without any further crashes).\r\n\r\nSo it looks like the \"crash\" happens once (or twice in a quick succession, to be more precise), and from there it seems fine no matter how hard I hammer the machine, until the next reboot.\r\n\r\nThat is, this is the full \"double crash\" that happens initially (latest main on Rawhide):\r\n```\r\n[ 3207.675737] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt98.mount.\r\n[ 3207.678658] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt99.mount.\r\n[ 3235.286101] systemd[1]: udisks2.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.287100] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.287478] avahi-daemon[736]: Got SIGTERM, quitting.\r\n[ 3235.287958] avahi-daemon[736]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv6 with address 2620:52:0:bb:f816:3eff:fe40:9445.\r\n[ 3235.288031] avahi-daemon[736]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface eth0.IPv4 with address 10.0.185.167.\r\n[ 3235.288085] avahi-daemon[736]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv6 with address ::1.\r\n[ 3235.288143] avahi-daemon[736]: Leaving mDNS multicast group on interface lo.IPv4 with address 127.0.0.1.\r\n[ 3235.292155] avahi-daemon[736]: avahi-daemon 0.8 exiting.\r\n[ 3235.340082] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[ 3235.340576] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=avahi-daemon comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[ 3235.438624] systemd[1]: systemd-logind.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.439286] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.550745] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[ 3235.551125] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=systemd-homed comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[ 3235.615132] audit: BPF prog-id=65 op=UNLOAD\r\n[ 3235.615330] systemd[1]: systemd-networkd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.615933] systemd[1]: systemd-resolved.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.616641] systemd[1]: systemd-hostnamed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.617218] systemd[1]: systemd-timesyncd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.617991] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3235.618489] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4647] caught SIGTERM, shutting down normally.\r\n[ 3235.619803] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4662] dhcp4 (eth0): canceled DHCP transaction\r\n[ 3235.619989] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4662] dhcp4 (eth0): activation: beginning transaction (timeout in 45 seconds)\r\n[ 3235.620112] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4663] dhcp4 (eth0): state changed no lease\r\n[ 3235.620417] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4668] manager: NetworkManager state is now CONNECTED_SITE\r\n[ 3235.624064] NetworkManager[760]: <info>  [1713649856.4705] exiting (success)\r\n[ 3235.673354] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[ 3235.673875] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=NetworkManager comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n...\r\n[ 3363.909334] systemd[1]: Unmounted tmp-mnt99.mount.\r\n[ 3364.013839] systemd[1]: user-runtime-dir@1001.service: Deactivated successfully.\r\n[ 3364.014048] systemd[1]: Stopped user-runtime-dir@1001.service.\r\n[ 3364.036622] audit[1]: SERVICE_STOP pid=1 uid=0 auid=4294967295 ses=4294967295 subj=system_u:system_r:init_t:s0 msg='unit=user-runtime-dir@1001 comm=\"systemd\" exe=\"/usr/lib/systemd/systemd\" hostname=? addr=? terminal=? res=success'\r\n[ 3369.808828] systemd[1]: udisks2.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809489] systemd[1]: avahi-daemon.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809588] systemd[1]: systemd-logind.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809672] systemd[1]: systemd-homed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809770] systemd[1]: systemd-networkd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809856] systemd[1]: systemd-resolved.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.809937] systemd[1]: systemd-hostnamed.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.810031] systemd[1]: systemd-timesyncd.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.810123] systemd[1]: NetworkManager.service: Unexpected error response from GetNameOwner(): Connection terminated\r\n[ 3369.812073] systemd[1]: Removed slice user-1001.slice.\r\n[ 3369.830819] systemd[1]: Started run-u65.service.\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd from now on there doesn't seem to be any similar \"crashes\" until the machine is rebooted.\n--- Comment by poettering ---\nLooks to me as if the broker kicks us off the bus. Maybe we hit some message limit, because of the many PropertiesChanged signals we generate or so?\r\n\r\nif you turn of debug logging in the broker, does it show anything interesting?\n--- Comment by mrc0mmand ---\nThis might be a slightly difficult (which is an issue in itself), but in the meantime the dbus-daemon logs show this just ~5 seconds before systems starts throwing errors:\r\n\r\n```\r\n[  974.472229] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt404.mount.\r\n[  974.500563] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt405.mount.\r\n[  974.523083] dbus-daemon[744]: [system] Failed to activate service 'org.freedesktop.systemd1': timed out (service_start_timeout=25000ms)\r\n[  974.527767] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt406.mount.\r\n[  974.555652] systemd[1]: Mounted tmp-mnt407.mount.\r\n```\n--- Comment by mrc0mmand ---\nYeah, there's a bunch of timeouts before the _kicking_ happens:\r\n\r\n```\r\n# journalctl -b -1 --no-pager --no-hostname -o short-monotonic _SYSTEMD_UNIT=dbus-daemon.service + PRIORITY=3\r\n[    4.395420] dbus-daemon[737]: [system] SELinux support is enabled\r\n[    6.449341] dbus-daemon[737]: [system] Activating via systemd: service name='org.freedesktop.hostname1' unit='dbus-org.freedesktop.hostname1.service' requested by '